AUDIO: 'All right, check this out. Every talking head tool I\'ve tested on this channel has had the same problem. They\'re VRAM monsters. You try running them on free Google Colab, they crash before they even finish loading. You try them locally without a high-end GPU, same'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'story. So, when I came across this new AI avatar lip sync tool, I had to dig in properly. And everything you\'re watching on screen right now, every single clip, was generated with it. The lip sync is'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clean, the head movement actually feels natural. And the best part? I got this running on the free T4 GPU in Google Colab. It took me days to crack, but the notebook is ready for you today, and I\'m'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to walk you through the whole thing. And I\'ll also show you a trick at the end that lets you squeeze out seriously high-quality results at fast speed, completely for free. So, stick around because that part alone is worth'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. So, the tool is called SoulX FlashHead, built by the AIGC team at Soul AI Lab. It\'s a 1.3 billion parameter model, and it ships in two versions. The light variant, on a single'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'RTX 4090, runs at 96 frames per second. That is real-time generation. You feed it audio, it\'s basically already done. The pro variant is slower, running at around 10.8 FPS on the same GPU, but you'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get noticeably better output quality and smoother head movement. Now, here\'s something interesting. If you check the Hugging Face repo, both models are almost identical in size. Light is 6. 11'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'GB, pro is 6.03 GB. The reason one is so much faster comes down to the VAE. Light uses the LTX VAE, fast and lean. Pro uses the WaN VAE, slower inference but'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'higher fidelity. Same weight on paper, completely different performance under the hood. All right, let me show you their official examples before we touch anything. First up, a dialogue between two talking heads, a male and female'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'speaking in turn. I\'ll play it now. Okay, see that? Every syllable is'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'landing cleanly. No floating mouth, no lag. And watch the head. There are actual natural tilts and shifts happening. It\'s not locked in place. That\'s genuinely impressive for a model this lightweight. Now, one thing I want'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to flag. I did try to replicate this dual face dialogue myself, and I couldn\'t produce both in a single generation. My best guess is they are going to release multi-character lip sync variant in future. I just want to'

